who discussed it with his colleague, Gavin Schmidt,

11
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
director of NASA's Institute for Space Studies.

12
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Here, Adam recalls their conversation for BBC World Service program, Crowd Science.

13
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.000
We know that there's been no other civilization on Earth,

14
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
and he stopped to be in said, how do you know that?

15
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
And my judge has dropped down to the floor.

16
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Adam's jaw dropped.

17
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
An idiom for when someone looked shocked and surprised.

18
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Could there have been a technologically advanced civilization before us here on Earth?

19
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:06.000
It may sound weird, but this idea has a scientific name.

20
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.000
Here is Caroline Steele, presenter of BBC's Crowd Science to explain.

21
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:19.000
The Cylurian hypothesis proposes that if there was a technologically advanced civilization hundreds of millions of years ago,

22
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.000
we wouldn't be able to find traces of it.

23
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:29.000
A hypothesis is an idea which explains how something happens and can be tested to find out if it's correct.

24
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
In this episode, we'll be discussing the Cylurian hypothesis.

25
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:44.000
The idea that a technologically advanced civilization existed before us on Earth, but vanished without leaving a trace.

26
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
As usual, we'll be learning some useful new words and idioms,

27
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:54.000
and remember you'll find all the vocabulary on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

28
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
But first, I have a question for you, Phil.

29
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Human civilization is thousands of years old, but the planet itself is much older.

30
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
So how old do scientists think the Earth is?

31
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Is it A, 3.5 billion years?

32
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
B, 4.5 billion years?

33
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Or C, 5.5 billion years?

34
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
I'm going to get C, 5.5 billion years.

35
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Okay, well, we will find the answer out later in the program.

36
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:30.000
To believe a technologically advanced civilization existed on Earth, hundreds of millions of years ago,

37
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
most people would probably want evidence.

38
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:40.000
We have evidence about other species from the past, such as the dinosaurs from fossils.

39
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:46.000
The remains of prehistoric plants or animals that have been preserved in rock for a very long time.

40
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
But according to Adam Frank, fossils won't help prove the Cylurian hypothesis.

41
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
As he explains here to BBC World Service program, crowd science.

42
00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Most things are not fossilized.

43
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:03.000
It's only a tiny fraction of Earth's life that has ever become fossilized.

44
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:12.000
So imagine that you have a 10,000 year long civilization, which is a blink of the eye for geology.

45
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
That's too short to really create a lot of fossils.

46
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Adam argues that only a tiny fraction, meaning a very small amount of life on Earth has turned into fossil.

47
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:31.000
In geological time, even a 10,000 year old civilization is the blink of an eye.

48
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.000
An idea meaning a very short period of time.

49
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:42.000
In other words, all the civilizations might have existed on Earth, but not for long enough to leave fossilized evidence.

50
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
However, not everyone is convinced by Adam's ideas.

51
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Evidence of our own civilization, including plastics and man-made materials like concrete, is already being layered into the Earth's crust.

52
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
And these are going to last a very long time.

53
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:07.000
So surely a technologically advanced civilization from prehistory would have left similar marks.

54
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Well, his Adam Frank again, answering these objections on BBC World Service program, crowd science.

55
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:24.000
What happens is somebody else will pick up on their work either affirming it and showing new evidence for it or pushing back on it.

56
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
As you get to like 20, 30, 40 papers, then you have a consensus.

57
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
You're like, okay, we've really, really looked at this. And now we don't.

58
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Adam welcomes new evidence, even evidence which contradicts his ideas as part of the scientific method needed to prove a hypothesis right or wrong.

59
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:48.000
It's how scientists form a consensus, meaning a general agreement about the issue.

60
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Personally, I think the idea of prehistoric civilizations on Earth is so mysterious.

61
00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:01.000
It's okay to keep an open mind. Now, isn't it time you reveal the answer to your question, Beth?

62
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:07.000
I think it is. I asked you how old just scientists think the Earth is.

63
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:14.000
You said five and a half billion years and I'm afraid you were wrongful. It's four and a half billion years.

64
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with the idiom, my jaw dropped, which is used to say someone looks very shocked and surprised.

65
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.000
A hypothesis is a suggestion that's proposed to explain something, which can then be tested to see if it's true.

66
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:38.000
Fossils are the remains of prehistoric plants or animals that have been preserved in rock for a very long time.

67
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
A tiny fraction of something is a very small amount of it.

68
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:46.000
The idiom, the blink of an eye, means a very short period of time.

69
00:05:46.000 --> 00:06:02.000
